e, England":"Market Deeping, Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wake","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","occupational name for ‘(man of) the watch’, from Middle English <i>wak</i>, <i>wake</i> ‘wake, vigil, watch, period of guard duty’ (Old English <i>wacu</i>, Old Norse <i>vaka</i>). It alternates with the synonymous Middle English <i>wache</i> (Old English <i>wacce</i>), hence the variant <b>Watch</b>. The surname was also interchangeable with   Waite   (the equivalent Old French term) which, like <i>Wake</i>, was sometimes translated as Latin <i>vigil</i> ‘(one who is) watchful, alert’. Compare the synonymous   Vail  . When the bearers had high social status, the surname probably denoted an officer with responsibility for the security of a castle, town, or royal person. Compare   Wakeman  .","variant of   Wack  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vail","meanings":["English: occupational name from Old French <i>de la veille</i> ‘of the watch, watchman’, with loss of <i>de</i>; compare   Wake  . There has been some confusion with the topographic name   Vale   and the nickname   Veal  .","Scottish: shortened and altered form of   McPhail  , Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Phàil</b> ‘son of Paul’.","Irish: variant of   Veale  ."]},{"name":"Waite","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): occupational name for a watchman, either in a town or castle, from Anglo-Norman French <i>waite</i> ‘watchman, member of the watch’ (of ancient Germanic origin; compare   Wachter  ). In the Middle Ages the town waits typically combined the functions of watchmen and musicians through being trumpeters or pipers. There may also have been some late confusion with   White   or   Wheat  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":8,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":33,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":46,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":55,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Wake was born in 1282, in Market Deeping, Lincolnshire, England. He married Alice Blisworth in 1312, in Blisworth, Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 daughters. He died in February 1348, at the age of 66, and was buried in Dowlish Wake, Somerset, England."},"et":{"Cir 1282–February 1348":"1282–veebruar 1348","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1321–1359":"1321–1359","1321–1364":"1321–1364","–1344":"–1344","1282–1348":"1282–1348","Living 1330":"1330","1282":"1282","1290":"1290","Cir 1282":"1282","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1348":"1348","1359":"1359","1312":"1312","1344":"1344","1300":"1300","1321":"1321","1453":"1453","1364":"1364","about 1321":"umbes 1321","February 1348":"veebruar 1348","16 January 1344":"1